ing with this question, Snyder makes the case that educators need to critically engage with issues of gender and power in order to create inclusive resources that meaningfully address the everyday messiness of law. As with all legal orders, gendered oppression can be perpetuated through Cree law, but Cree law is also a dynamic resource for challenging gendered oppression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCree IndiansxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aCree IndianszCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aCree womenxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aCree womenzCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aCree women-Legal status, laws, etc.-Canada. 0aFeminist jurisprudencezCanada. 0aIndians in mass media. 0aIndigenous peoples and mass media. 0aLaw in mass media. 0aNative peoples in mass media. 0aWomen in mass media. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311141792940uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483570140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774835701423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774835701/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-141792-9  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles